2531 /**
2532  * cgroup_migrate_finish - cleanup after attach
2533  * @mgctx: migration context
2534  *
2535  * Undo cgroup_migrate_add_src() and cgroup_migrate_prepare_dst().  See
2536  * those functions for details.
2537  */
2538 void cgroup_migrate_finish(struct cgroup_mgctx *mgctx)
     /*   */
2539 {
2540         LIST_HEAD(preloaded);
2541         struct css_set *cset, *tmp_cset;
2542 
2543         lockdep_assert_held(&cgroup_mutex);
2544 
2545         spin_lock_irq(&css_set_lock);
2546 
2547         list_splice_tail_init(&mgctx->preloaded_src_csets, &preloaded);
2548         list_splice_tail_init(&mgctx->preloaded_dst_csets, &preloaded);
2549 
2550         list_for_each_entry_safe(cset, tmp_cset, &preloaded, mg_preload_node) {
2551                 cset->mg_src_cgrp = NULL;
2552                 cset->mg_dst_cgrp = NULL;
2553                 cset->mg_dst_cset = NULL;
2554                 list_del_init(&cset->mg_preload_node);
2555                 put_css_set_locked(cset);
2556         }
2557 
2558         spin_unlock_irq(&css_set_lock);
2559 }

2561 /**
2562  * cgroup_migrate_add_src - add a migration source css_set
2563  * @src_cset: the source css_set to add
2564  * @dst_cgrp: the destination cgroup
2565  * @mgctx: migration context
2566  *
2567  * Tasks belonging to @src_cset are about to be migrated to @dst_cgrp.  Pin
2568  * @src_cset and add it to @mgctx->src_csets, which should later be cleaned
2569  * up by cgroup_migrate_finish().
2570  *
2571  * This function may be called without holding cgroup_threadgroup_rwsem
2572  * even if the target is a process.  Threads may be created and destroyed
2573  * but as long as cgroup_mutex is not dropped, no new css_set can be put
2574  * into play and the preloaded css_sets are guaranteed to cover all
2575  * migrations.
2576  */
2577 void cgroup_migrate_add_src(struct css_set *src_cset,
     /*   */
2578                             struct cgroup *dst_cgrp,
2579                             struct cgroup_mgctx *mgctx)
2580 {
2581         struct cgroup *src_cgrp;
2582 
2583         lockdep_assert_held(&cgroup_mutex);
2584         lockdep_assert_held(&css_set_lock);
2585 
2586         /*
2587          * If ->dead, @src_set is associated with one or more dead cgroups
2588          * and doesn't contain any migratable tasks.  Ignore it early so
2589          * that the rest of migration path doesn't get confused by it.
2590          */
2591         if (src_cset->dead)
2592                 return;
2593 
2594         src_cgrp = cset_cgroup_from_root(src_cset, dst_cgrp->root);
2595 
2596         if (!list_empty(&src_cset->mg_preload_node))
2597                 return;
2598 
2599         WARN_ON(src_cset->mg_src_cgrp);
2600         WARN_ON(src_cset->mg_dst_cgrp);
2601         WARN_ON(!list_empty(&src_cset->mg_tasks));
2602         WARN_ON(!list_empty(&src_cset->mg_node));
2603 
2604         src_cset->mg_src_cgrp = src_cgrp;
2605         src_cset->mg_dst_cgrp = dst_cgrp;
2606         get_css_set(src_cset);
2607         list_add_tail(&src_cset->mg_preload_node, &mgctx->preloaded_src_csets);
2608 }
2609 
2610 /**
2611  * cgroup_migrate_prepare_dst - prepare destination css_sets for migration
2612  * @mgctx: migration context
2613  *
2614  * Tasks are about to be moved and all the source css_sets have been
2615  * preloaded to @mgctx->preloaded_src_csets.  This function looks up and
2616  * pins all destination css_sets, links each to its source, and append them
2617  * to @mgctx->preloaded_dst_csets.
2618  *
2619  * This function must be called after cgroup_migrate_add_src() has been
2620  * called on each migration source css_set.  After migration is performed
2621  * using cgroup_migrate(), cgroup_migrate_finish() must be called on
2622  * @mgctx.
2623  */
2624 int cgroup_migrate_prepare_dst(struct cgroup_mgctx *mgctx)
     /*   */
2625 {
2626         struct css_set *src_cset, *tmp_cset;
2627 
2628         lockdep_assert_held(&cgroup_mutex);
2629 
2630         /* look up the dst cset for each src cset and link it to src */
2631         list_for_each_entry_safe(src_cset, tmp_cset, &mgctx->preloaded_src_csets,
2632                                  mg_preload_node) {
2633                 struct css_set *dst_cset;
2634                 struct cgroup_subsys *ss;
2635                 int ssid;
2636 
2637                 dst_cset = find_css_set(src_cset, src_cset->mg_dst_cgrp);
2638                 if (!dst_cset)
2639                         return -ENOMEM;
2640 
2641                 WARN_ON_ONCE(src_cset->mg_dst_cset || dst_cset->mg_dst_cset);
2642 
2643                 /*
2644                  * If src cset equals dst, it's noop.  Drop the src.
2645                  * cgroup_migrate() will skip the cset too.  Note that we
2646                  * can't handle src == dst as some nodes are used by both.
2647                  */
2648                 if (src_cset == dst_cset) {
2649                         src_cset->mg_src_cgrp = NULL;
2650                         src_cset->mg_dst_cgrp = NULL;
2651                         list_del_init(&src_cset->mg_preload_node);
2652                         put_css_set(src_cset);
2653                         put_css_set(dst_cset);
2654                         continue;
2655                 }
2656 
2657                 src_cset->mg_dst_cset = dst_cset;
2658 
2659                 if (list_empty(&dst_cset->mg_preload_node))
2660                         list_add_tail(&dst_cset->mg_preload_node,
2661                                       &mgctx->preloaded_dst_csets);
2662                 else
2663                         put_css_set(dst_cset);
2664 
2665                 for_each_subsys(ss, ssid)
2666                         if (src_cset->subsys[ssid] != dst_cset->subsys[ssid])
2667                                 mgctx->ss_mask |= 1 << ssid;
2668         }
2669 
2670         return 0;
2671 }

2673 /**
2674  * cgroup_migrate - migrate a process or task to a cgroup
2675  * @leader: the leader of the process or the task to migrate
2676  * @threadgroup: whether @leader points to the whole process or a single task
2677  * @mgctx: migration context
2678  *
2679  * Migrate a process or task denoted by @leader.  If migrating a process,
2680  * the caller must be holding cgroup_threadgroup_rwsem.  The caller is also
2681  * responsible for invoking cgroup_migrate_add_src() and
2682  * cgroup_migrate_prepare_dst() on the targets before invoking this
2683  * function and following up with cgroup_migrate_finish().
2684  *
2685  * As long as a controller's ->can_attach() doesn't fail, this function is
2686  * guaranteed to succeed.  This means that, excluding ->can_attach()
2687  * failure, when migrating multiple targets, the success or failure can be
2688  * decided for all targets by invoking group_migrate_prepare_dst() before
2689  * actually starting migrating.
2690  */
2691 int cgroup_migrate(struct task_struct *leader, bool threadgroup,
     /*   */
2692                    struct cgroup_mgctx *mgctx)
2693 {
2694         struct task_struct *task;
2695 
2696         /*
2697          * Prevent freeing of tasks while we take a snapshot. Tasks that are
2698          * already PF_EXITING could be freed from underneath us unless we
2699          * take an rcu_read_lock.
2700          */
2701         spin_lock_irq(&css_set_lock);
2702         rcu_read_lock();
2703         task = leader;
2704         do {
2705                 cgroup_migrate_add_task(task, mgctx);
2706                 if (!threadgroup)
2707                         break;
2708         } while_each_thread(leader, task);
2709         rcu_read_unlock();
2710         spin_unlock_irq(&css_set_lock);
2711 
2712         return cgroup_migrate_execute(mgctx);
2713 }
2714 
2715 /**
2716  * cgroup_attach_task - attach a task or a whole threadgroup to a cgroup
2717  * @dst_cgrp: the cgroup to attach to
2718  * @leader: the task or the leader of the threadgroup to be attached
2719  * @threadgroup: attach the whole threadgroup?
2720  *
2721  * Call holding cgroup_mutex and cgroup_threadgroup_rwsem.
2722  */
2723 int cgroup_attach_task(struct cgroup *dst_cgrp, struct task_struct *leader,
     /*   */
2724                        bool threadgroup)
2725 {
2726         DEFINE_CGROUP_MGCTX(mgctx);
2727         struct task_struct *task;
2728         int ret = 0;
2729 
2730         /* look up all src csets */
2731         spin_lock_irq(&css_set_lock);
2732         rcu_read_lock();
2733         task = leader;
2734         do {
2735                 cgroup_migrate_add_src(task_css_set(task), dst_cgrp, &mgctx);
2736                 if (!threadgroup)
2737                         break;
2738         } while_each_thread(leader, task);
2739         rcu_read_unlock();
2740         spin_unlock_irq(&css_set_lock);
2741 
2742         /* prepare dst csets and commit */
2743         ret = cgroup_migrate_prepare_dst(&mgctx);
2744         if (!ret)
2745                 ret = cgroup_migrate(leader, threadgroup, &mgctx);
2746 
2747         cgroup_migrate_finish(&mgctx);
2748 
2749         if (!ret)
2750                 TRACE_CGROUP_PATH(attach_task, dst_cgrp, leader, threadgroup);
2751 
2752         return ret;
2753 }
2754 
2755 struct task_struct *cgroup_procs_write_start(char *buf, bool threadgroup,
     /*   */
2756                                              bool *locked,
2757                                              struct cgroup *dst_cgrp)
2758         __acquires(&cgroup_threadgroup_rwsem)
2759 {
2760         struct task_struct *tsk;
2761         pid_t pid;
2762         bool force_migration = false;
2763 
2764         if (kstrtoint(strstrip(buf), 0, &pid) || pid < 0)
2765                 return ERR_PTR(-EINVAL);
2766 
2767         /*
2768          * If we migrate a single thread, we don't care about threadgroup
2769          * stability. If the thread is `current`, it won't exit(2) under our
2770          * hands or change PID through exec(2). We exclude
2771          * cgroup_update_dfl_csses and other cgroup_{proc,thread}s_write
2772          * callers by cgroup_mutex.
2773          * Therefore, we can skip the global lock.
2774          */
2775         lockdep_assert_held(&cgroup_mutex);
2776         if (pid || threadgroup) {
2777                 percpu_down_write(&cgroup_threadgroup_rwsem);
2778                 *locked = true;
2779         } else {
2780                 *locked = false;
2781         }
2782 
2783         rcu_read_lock();
2784         if (pid) {
2785                 tsk = find_task_by_vpid(pid);
2786                 if (!tsk) {
2787                         tsk = ERR_PTR(-ESRCH);
2788                         goto out_unlock_threadgroup;
2789                 }
2790         } else {
2791                 tsk = current;
2792         }
2793 
2794         if (threadgroup)
2795                 tsk = tsk->group_leader;
2796 
2797         if (tsk->flags & PF_KTHREAD)
2798                 trace_android_rvh_cgroup_force_kthread_migration(tsk, dst_cgrp, &force_migration);
2799 
2800         /*
2801          * kthreads may acquire PF_NO_SETAFFINITY during initialization.
2802          * If userland migrates such a kthread to a non-root cgroup, it can
2803          * become trapped in a cpuset, or RT kthread may be born in a
2804          * cgroup with no rt_runtime allocated.  Just say no.
2805          */
2806         if (!force_migration && (tsk->no_cgroup_migration || (tsk->flags & PF_NO_SETAFFINITY))) {
2807                 tsk = ERR_PTR(-EINVAL);
2808                 goto out_unlock_threadgroup;
2809         }
2810 
2811         get_task_struct(tsk);
2812         goto out_unlock_rcu;
2813 
2814 out_unlock_threadgroup:
2815         if (*locked) {
2816                 percpu_up_write(&cgroup_threadgroup_rwsem);
2817                 *locked = false;
2818         }
2819 out_unlock_rcu:
2820         rcu_read_unlock();
2821         return tsk;
2822 }

     /*   */
2825         __releases(&cgroup_threadgroup_rwsem)
2826 {
2827         struct cgroup_subsys *ss;
2828         int ssid;
2829 
2830         /* release reference from cgroup_procs_write_start() */
2831         put_task_struct(task);
2832 
2833         if (locked)
2834                 percpu_up_write(&cgroup_threadgroup_rwsem);
2835         for_each_subsys(ss, ssid)
2836                 if (ss->post_attach)
2837                         ss->post_attach();
2838 }

2874 /**
2875  * cgroup_update_dfl_csses - update css assoc of a subtree in default hierarchy
2876  * @cgrp: root of the subtree to update csses for
2877  *
2878  * @cgrp's control masks have changed and its subtree's css associations
2879  * need to be updated accordingly.  This function looks up all css_sets
2880  * which are attached to the subtree, creates the matching updated css_sets
2881  * and migrates the tasks to the new ones.
2882  */
2883 static int cgroup_update_dfl_csses(struct cgroup *cgrp)
     /*   */
2884 {
2885         DEFINE_CGROUP_MGCTX(mgctx);
2886         struct cgroup_subsys_state *d_css;
2887         struct cgroup *dsct;
2888         struct css_set *src_cset;
2889         int ret;
2890 
2891         lockdep_assert_held(&cgroup_mutex);
2892 
2893         percpu_down_write(&cgroup_threadgroup_rwsem);
2894 
2895         /* look up all csses currently attached to @cgrp's subtree */
2896         spin_lock_irq(&css_set_lock);
2897         cgroup_for_each_live_descendant_pre(dsct, d_css, cgrp) {
2898                 struct cgrp_cset_link *link;
2899 
2900                 list_for_each_entry(link, &dsct->cset_links, cset_link)
2901                         cgroup_migrate_add_src(link->cset, dsct, &mgctx);
2902         }
2903         spin_unlock_irq(&css_set_lock);
2904 
2905         /* NULL dst indicates self on default hierarchy */
2906         ret = cgroup_migrate_prepare_dst(&mgctx);
2907         if (ret)
2908                 goto out_finish;
2909 
2910         spin_lock_irq(&css_set_lock);
2911         list_for_each_entry(src_cset, &mgctx.preloaded_src_csets, mg_preload_node) {
2912                 struct task_struct *task, *ntask;
2913 
2914                 /* all tasks in src_csets need to be migrated */
2915                 list_for_each_entry_safe(task, ntask, &src_cset->tasks, cg_list)
2916                         cgroup_migrate_add_task(task, &mgctx);
2917         }
2918         spin_unlock_irq(&css_set_lock);
2919 
2920         ret = cgroup_migrate_execute(&mgctx);
2921 out_finish:
2922         cgroup_migrate_finish(&mgctx);
2923         percpu_up_write(&cgroup_threadgroup_rwsem);
2924         return ret;
2925 }

2927 /**
2928  * cgroup_lock_and_drain_offline - lock cgroup_mutex and drain offlined csses
2929  * @cgrp: root of the target subtree
2930  *
2931  * Because css offlining is asynchronous, userland may try to re-enable a
2932  * controller while the previous css is still around.  This function grabs
2933  * cgroup_mutex and drains the previous css instances of @cgrp's subtree.
2934  */
2935 void cgroup_lock_and_drain_offline(struct cgroup *cgrp)
     /*   */
2936         __acquires(&cgroup_mutex)
2937 {
2938         struct cgroup *dsct;
2939         struct cgroup_subsys_state *d_css;
2940         struct cgroup_subsys *ss;
2941         int ssid;
2942 
2943 restart:
2944         mutex_lock(&cgroup_mutex);
2945 
2946         cgroup_for_each_live_descendant_post(dsct, d_css, cgrp) {
2947                 for_each_subsys(ss, ssid) {
2948                         struct cgroup_subsys_state *css = cgroup_css(dsct, ss);
2949                         DEFINE_WAIT(wait);
2950 
2951                         if (!css || !percpu_ref_is_dying(&css->refcnt))
2952                                 continue;
2953 
2954                         cgroup_get_live(dsct);
2955                         prepare_to_wait(&dsct->offline_waitq, &wait,
2956                                         TASK_UNINTERRUPTIBLE);
2957 
2958                         mutex_unlock(&cgroup_mutex);
2959                         schedule();
2960                         finish_wait(&dsct->offline_waitq, &wait);
2961 
2962                         cgroup_put(dsct);
2963                         goto restart;
2964                 }
2965         }
2966 }

3029 static bool css_visible(struct cgroup_subsys_state *css)
     /*   */
3030 {
3031         struct cgroup_subsys *ss = css->ss;
3032         struct cgroup *cgrp = css->cgroup;
3033 
3034         if (cgroup_control(cgrp) & (1 << ss->id))
3035                 return true;
3036         if (!(cgroup_ss_mask(cgrp) & (1 << ss->id)))
3037                 return false;
3038         return cgroup_on_dfl(cgrp) && ss->implicit_on_dfl;
3039 }

3041 /**
3042  * cgroup_apply_control_enable - enable or show csses according to control
3043  * @cgrp: root of the target subtree
3044  *
3045  * Walk @cgrp's subtree and create new csses or make the existing ones
3046  * visible.  A css is created invisible if it's being implicitly enabled
3047  * through dependency.  An invisible css is made visible when the userland
3048  * explicitly enables it.
3049  *
3050  * Returns 0 on success, -errno on failure.  On failure, csses which have
3051  * been processed already aren't cleaned up.  The caller is responsible for
3052  * cleaning up with cgroup_apply_control_disable().
3053  */
3054 static int cgroup_apply_control_enable(struct cgroup *cgrp)
     /*   */
3055 {
3056         struct cgroup *dsct;
3057         struct cgroup_subsys_state *d_css;
3058         struct cgroup_subsys *ss;
3059         int ssid, ret;
3060 
3061         cgroup_for_each_live_descendant_pre(dsct, d_css, cgrp) {
3062                 for_each_subsys(ss, ssid) {
3063                         struct cgroup_subsys_state *css = cgroup_css(dsct, ss);
3064 
3065                         if (!(cgroup_ss_mask(dsct) & (1 << ss->id)))
3066                                 continue;
3067 
3068                         if (!css) {
3069                                 css = css_create(dsct, ss);
3070                                 if (IS_ERR(css))
3071                                         return PTR_ERR(css);
3072                         }
3073 
3074                         WARN_ON_ONCE(percpu_ref_is_dying(&css->refcnt));
3075 
3076                         if (css_visible(css)) {
3077                                 ret = css_populate_dir(css);
3078                                 if (ret)
3079                                         return ret;
3080                         }
3081                 }
3082         }
3083 
3084         return 0;
3085 }

3087 /**
3088  * cgroup_apply_control_disable - kill or hide csses according to control
3089  * @cgrp: root of the target subtree
3090  *
3091  * Walk @cgrp's subtree and kill and hide csses so that they match
3092  * cgroup_ss_mask() and cgroup_visible_mask().
3093  *
3094  * A css is hidden when the userland requests it to be disabled while other
3095  * subsystems are still depending on it.  The css must not actively control
3096  * resources and be in the vanilla state if it's made visible again later.
3097  * Controllers which may be depended upon should provide ->css_reset() for
3098  * this purpose.
3099  */
3100 static void cgroup_apply_control_disable(struct cgroup *cgrp)
     /*   */
3101 {
3102         struct cgroup *dsct;
3103         struct cgroup_subsys_state *d_css;
3104         struct cgroup_subsys *ss;
3105         int ssid;
3106 
3107         cgroup_for_each_live_descendant_post(dsct, d_css, cgrp) {
3108                 for_each_subsys(ss, ssid) {
3109                         struct cgroup_subsys_state *css = cgroup_css(dsct, ss);
3110 
3111                         if (!css)
3112                                 continue;
3113 
3114                         WARN_ON_ONCE(percpu_ref_is_dying(&css->refcnt));
3115 
3116                         if (css->parent &&
3117                             !(cgroup_ss_mask(dsct) & (1 << ss->id))) {
3118                                 kill_css(css);
3119                         } else if (!css_visible(css)) {
3120                                 css_clear_dir(css);
3121                                 if (ss->css_reset)
3122                                         ss->css_reset(css);
3123                         }
3124                 }
3125         }
3126 }

3128 /**
3129  * cgroup_apply_control - apply control mask updates to the subtree
3130  * @cgrp: root of the target subtree
3131  *
3132  * subsystems can be enabled and disabled in a subtree using the following
3133  * steps.
3134  *
3135  * 1. Call cgroup_save_control() to stash the current state.
3136  * 2. Update ->subtree_control masks in the subtree as desired.
3137  * 3. Call cgroup_apply_control() to apply the changes.
3138  * 4. Optionally perform other related operations.
3139  * 5. Call cgroup_finalize_control() to finish up.
3140  *
3141  * This function implements step 3 and propagates the mask changes
3142  * throughout @cgrp's subtree, updates csses accordingly and perform
3143  * process migrations.
3144  */
3145 static int cgroup_apply_control(struct cgroup *cgrp)
     /*   */
3146 {
3147         int ret;
3148 
3149         cgroup_propagate_control(cgrp);
3150 
3151         ret = cgroup_apply_control_enable(cgrp);
3152         if (ret)
3153                 return ret;
3154 
3155         /*
3156          * At this point, cgroup_e_css_by_mask() results reflect the new csses
3157          * making the following cgroup_update_dfl_csses() properly update
3158          * css associations of all tasks in the subtree.
3159          */
3160         ret = cgroup_update_dfl_csses(cgrp);
3161         if (ret)
3162                 return ret;
3163 
3164         return 0;
3165 }
3166 
3167 /**
3168  * cgroup_finalize_control - finalize control mask update
3169  * @cgrp: root of the target subtree
3170  * @ret: the result of the update
3171  *
3172  * Finalize control mask update.  See cgroup_apply_control() for more info.
3173  */
3174 static void cgroup_finalize_control(struct cgroup *cgrp, int ret)
     /*   */
3175 {
3176         if (ret) {
3177                 cgroup_restore_control(cgrp);
3178                 cgroup_propagate_control(cgrp);
3179         }
3180 
3181         cgroup_apply_control_disable(cgrp);
3182 }
3183 
3184 static int cgroup_vet_subtree_control_enable(struct cgroup *cgrp, u16 enable)
     /*   */
3185 {
3186         u16 domain_enable = enable & ~cgrp_dfl_threaded_ss_mask;
3187 
3188         /* if nothing is getting enabled, nothing to worry about */
3189         if (!enable)
3190                 return 0;
3191 
3192         /* can @cgrp host any resources? */
3193         if (!cgroup_is_valid_domain(cgrp->dom_cgrp))
3194                 return -EOPNOTSUPP;
3195 
3196         /* mixables don't care */
3197         if (cgroup_is_mixable(cgrp))
3198                 return 0;
3199 
3200         if (domain_enable) {
3201                 /* can't enable domain controllers inside a thread subtree */
3202                 if (cgroup_is_thread_root(cgrp) || cgroup_is_threaded(cgrp))
3203                         return -EOPNOTSUPP;
3204         } else {
3205                 /*
3206                  * Threaded controllers can handle internal competitions
3207                  * and are always allowed inside a (prospective) thread
3208                  * subtree.
3209                  */
3210                 if (cgroup_can_be_thread_root(cgrp) || cgroup_is_threaded(cgrp))
3211                         return 0;
3212         }
3213 
3214         /*
3215          * Controllers can't be enabled for a cgroup with tasks to avoid
3216          * child cgroups competing against tasks.
3217          */
3218         if (cgroup_has_tasks(cgrp))
3219                 return -EBUSY;
3220 
3221         return 0;
3222 }

3224 /* change the enabled child controllers for a cgroup in the default hierarchy */
3225 static ssize_t cgroup_subtree_control_write(struct kernfs_open_file *of,
     /*   */
3226                                             char *buf, size_t nbytes,
3227                                             loff_t off)
3228 {
3229         u16 enable = 0, disable = 0;
3230         struct cgroup *cgrp, *child;
3231         struct cgroup_subsys *ss;
3232         char *tok;
3233         int ssid, ret;
3234 
3235         /*
3236          * Parse input - space separated list of subsystem names prefixed
3237          * with either + or -.
3238          */
3239         buf = strstrip(buf);
3240         while ((tok = strsep(&buf, " "))) {
3241                 if (tok[0] == '\0')
3242                         continue;
3243                 do_each_subsys_mask(ss, ssid, ~cgrp_dfl_inhibit_ss_mask) {
3244                         if (!cgroup_ssid_enabled(ssid) ||
3245                             strcmp(tok + 1, ss->name))
3246                                 continue;
3247 
3248                         if (*tok == '+') {
3249                                 enable |= 1 << ssid;
3250                                 disable &= ~(1 << ssid);
3251                         } else if (*tok == '-') {
3252                                 disable |= 1 << ssid;
3253                                 enable &= ~(1 << ssid);
3254                         } else {
3255                                 return -EINVAL;
3256                         }
3257                         break;
3258                 } while_each_subsys_mask();
3259                 if (ssid == CGROUP_SUBSYS_COUNT)
3260                         return -EINVAL;
3261         }
3262 
3263         cgrp = cgroup_kn_lock_live(of->kn, true);
3264         if (!cgrp)
3265                 return -ENODEV;
3266 
3267         for_each_subsys(ss, ssid) {
3268                 if (enable & (1 << ssid)) {
3269                         if (cgrp->subtree_control & (1 << ssid)) {
3270                                 enable &= ~(1 << ssid);
3271                                 continue;
3272                         }
3273 
3274                         if (!(cgroup_control(cgrp) & (1 << ssid))) {
3275                                 ret = -ENOENT;
3276                                 goto out_unlock;
3277                         }
3278                 } else if (disable & (1 << ssid)) {
3279                         if (!(cgrp->subtree_control & (1 << ssid))) {
3280                                 disable &= ~(1 << ssid);
3281                                 continue;
3282                         }
3283 
3284                         /* a child has it enabled? */
3285                         cgroup_for_each_live_child(child, cgrp) {
3286                                 if (child->subtree_control & (1 << ssid)) {
3287                                         ret = -EBUSY;
3288                                         goto out_unlock;
3289                                 }
3290                         }
3291                 }
3292         }
3293 
3294         if (!enable && !disable) {
3295                 ret = 0;
3296                 goto out_unlock;
3297         }
3298 
3299         ret = cgroup_vet_subtree_control_enable(cgrp, enable);
3300         if (ret)
3301                 goto out_unlock;
3302 
3303         /* save and update control masks and prepare csses */
3304         cgroup_save_control(cgrp);
3305 
3306         cgrp->subtree_control |= enable;
3307         cgrp->subtree_control &= ~disable;
3308 
3309         ret = cgroup_apply_control(cgrp);
3310         cgroup_finalize_control(cgrp, ret);
3311         if (ret)
3312                 goto out_unlock;
3313 
3314         kernfs_activate(cgrp->kn);
3315 out_unlock:
3316         cgroup_kn_unlock(of->kn);
3317         return ret ?: nbytes;
3318 }

3320 /**
3321  * cgroup_enable_threaded - make @cgrp threaded
3322  * @cgrp: the target cgroup
3323  *
3324  * Called when "threaded" is written to the cgroup.type interface file and
3325  * tries to make @cgrp threaded and join the parent's resource domain.
3326  * This function is never called on the root cgroup as cgroup.type doesn't
3327  * exist on it.
3328  */
3329 static int cgroup_enable_threaded(struct cgroup *cgrp)
     /*   */
3330 {
3331         struct cgroup *parent = cgroup_parent(cgrp);
3332         struct cgroup *dom_cgrp = parent->dom_cgrp;
3333         struct cgroup *dsct;
3334         struct cgroup_subsys_state *d_css;
3335         int ret;
3336 
3337         lockdep_assert_held(&cgroup_mutex);
3338 
3339         /* noop if already threaded */
3340         if (cgroup_is_threaded(cgrp))
3341                 return 0;
3342 
3343         /*
3344          * If @cgroup is populated or has domain controllers enabled, it
3345          * can't be switched.  While the below cgroup_can_be_thread_root()
3346          * test can catch the same conditions, that's only when @parent is
3347          * not mixable, so let's check it explicitly.
3348          */
3349         if (cgroup_is_populated(cgrp) ||
3350             cgrp->subtree_control & ~cgrp_dfl_threaded_ss_mask)
3351                 return -EOPNOTSUPP;
3352 
3353         /* we're joining the parent's domain, ensure its validity */
3354         if (!cgroup_is_valid_domain(dom_cgrp) ||
3355             !cgroup_can_be_thread_root(dom_cgrp))
3356                 return -EOPNOTSUPP;
3357 
3358         /*
3359          * The following shouldn't cause actual migrations and should
3360          * always succeed.
3361          */
3362         cgroup_save_control(cgrp);
3363 
3364         cgroup_for_each_live_descendant_pre(dsct, d_css, cgrp)
3365                 if (dsct == cgrp || cgroup_is_threaded(dsct))
3366                         dsct->dom_cgrp = dom_cgrp;
3367 
3368         ret = cgroup_apply_control(cgrp);
3369         if (!ret)
3370                 parent->nr_threaded_children++;
3371 
3372         cgroup_finalize_control(cgrp, ret);
3373         return ret;
3374 }

3376 static int cgroup_type_show(struct seq_file *seq, void *v)
     /*   */
3377 {
3378         struct cgroup *cgrp = seq_css(seq)->cgroup;
3379 
3380         if (cgroup_is_threaded(cgrp))
3381                 seq_puts(seq, "threaded\n");
3382         else if (!cgroup_is_valid_domain(cgrp))
3383                 seq_puts(seq, "domain invalid\n");
3384         else if (cgroup_is_thread_root(cgrp))
3385                 seq_puts(seq, "domain threaded\n");
3386         else
3387                 seq_puts(seq, "domain\n");
3388 
3389         return 0;
3390 }

3392 static ssize_t cgroup_type_write(struct kernfs_open_file *of, char *buf,
     /*   */
3393                                  size_t nbytes, loff_t off)
3394 {
3395         struct cgroup *cgrp;
3396         int ret;
3397 
3398         /* only switching to threaded mode is supported */
3399         if (strcmp(strstrip(buf), "threaded"))
3400                 return -EINVAL;
3401 
3402         /* drain dying csses before we re-apply (threaded) subtree control */
3403         cgrp = cgroup_kn_lock_live(of->kn, true);
3404         if (!cgrp)
3405                 return -ENOENT;
3406 
3407         /* threaded can only be enabled */
3408         ret = cgroup_enable_threaded(cgrp);
3409 
3410         cgroup_kn_unlock(of->kn);
3411         return ret ?: nbytes;
3412 }

3576 static ssize_t cgroup_pressure_write(struct kernfs_open_file *of, char *buf,
     /*   */
3577                                           size_t nbytes, enum psi_res res)
3578 {

3584         if (!cgrp)
3585                 return -ENODEV;

3599         cgroup_put(cgrp);
3600 
3601         return nbytes;
3602 }

3688 static ssize_t cgroup_file_write(struct kernfs_open_file *of, char *buf,
     /*   */
3689                                  size_t nbytes, loff_t off)
3690 {
3691         struct cgroup_namespace *ns = current->nsproxy->cgroup_ns;
3692         struct cgroup *cgrp = of->kn->parent->priv;
3693         struct cftype *cft = of->kn->priv;
3694         struct cgroup_subsys_state *css;
3695         int ret;
3696 
3697         if (!nbytes)
3698                 return 0;
3699 
3700         /*
3701          * If namespaces are delegation boundaries, disallow writes to
3702          * files in an non-init namespace root from inside the namespace
3703          * except for the files explicitly marked delegatable -
3704          * cgroup.procs and cgroup.subtree_control.
3705          */
3706         if ((cgrp->root->flags & CGRP_ROOT_NS_DELEGATE) &&
3707             !(cft->flags & CFTYPE_NS_DELEGATABLE) &&
3708             ns != &init_cgroup_ns && ns->root_cset->dfl_cgrp == cgrp)
3709                 return -EPERM;
3710 
3711         if (cft->write)
3712                 return cft->write(of, buf, nbytes, off);
3713 
3714         /*
3715          * kernfs guarantees that a file isn't deleted with operations in
3716          * flight, which means that the matching css is and stays alive and
3717          * doesn't need to be pinned.  The RCU locking is not necessary
3718          * either.  It's just for the convenience of using cgroup_css().
3719          */
3720         rcu_read_lock();
3721         css = cgroup_css(cgrp, cft->ss);
3722         rcu_read_unlock();
3723 
3724         if (cft->write_u64) {
3725                 unsigned long long v;
3726                 ret = kstrtoull(buf, 0, &v);
3727                 if (!ret)
3728                         ret = cft->write_u64(css, cft, v);
3729         } else if (cft->write_s64) {
3730                 long long v;
3731                 ret = kstrtoll(buf, 0, &v);
3732                 if (!ret)
3733                         ret = cft->write_s64(css, cft, v);
3734         } else {
3735                 ret = -EINVAL;
3736         }
3737 
3738         return ret ?: nbytes;
3739 }

3805 /* set uid and gid of cgroup dirs and files to that of the creator */

     /*   */
3807 {

3809                                .ia_uid = current_fsuid(),

3825 static int cgroup_add_file(struct cgroup_subsys_state *css, struct cgroup *cgrp,
     /*   */
3826                            struct cftype *cft)
3827 {
3828         char name[CGROUP_FILE_NAME_MAX];
3829         struct kernfs_node *kn;
3830         struct lock_class_key *key = NULL;
3831         int ret;
3832 
3833 #ifdef CONFIG_DEBUG_LOCK_ALLOC
3834         key = &cft->lockdep_key;
3835 #endif
3836         kn = __kernfs_create_file(cgrp->kn, cgroup_file_name(cgrp, cft, name),
3837                                   cgroup_file_mode(cft),
3838                                   GLOBAL_ROOT_UID, GLOBAL_ROOT_GID,
3839                                   0, cft->kf_ops, cft,
3840                                   NULL, key);
3841         if (IS_ERR(kn))
3842                 return PTR_ERR(kn);
3843 
3844         ret = cgroup_kn_set_ugid(kn);
3845         if (ret) {
3846                 kernfs_remove(kn);
3847                 return ret;
3848         }
3849 
3850         if (cft->file_offset) {
3851                 struct cgroup_file *cfile = (void *)css + cft->file_offset;
3852 
3853                 timer_setup(&cfile->notify_timer, cgroup_file_notify_timer, 0);
3854 
3855                 spin_lock_irq(&cgroup_file_kn_lock);
3856                 cfile->kn = kn;
3857                 spin_unlock_irq(&cgroup_file_kn_lock);
3858         }
3859 
3860         return 0;
3861 }

3863 /**
3864  * cgroup_addrm_files - add or remove files to a cgroup directory
3865  * @css: the target css
3866  * @cgrp: the target cgroup (usually css->cgroup)
3867  * @cfts: array of cftypes to be added
3868  * @is_add: whether to add or remove
3869  *
3870  * Depending on @is_add, add or remove files defined by @cfts on @cgrp.
3871  * For removals, this function never fails.
3872  */
3873 static int cgroup_addrm_files(struct cgroup_subsys_state *css,
     /*   */
3874                               struct cgroup *cgrp, struct cftype cfts[],
3875                               bool is_add)
3876 {
3877         struct cftype *cft, *cft_end = NULL;
3878         int ret = 0;
3879 
3880         lockdep_assert_held(&cgroup_mutex);
3881 
3882 restart:
3883         for (cft = cfts; cft != cft_end && cft->name[0] != '\0'; cft++) {
3884                 /* does cft->flags tell us to skip this file on @cgrp? */
3885                 if ((cft->flags & __CFTYPE_ONLY_ON_DFL) && !cgroup_on_dfl(cgrp))
3886                         continue;
3887                 if ((cft->flags & __CFTYPE_NOT_ON_DFL) && cgroup_on_dfl(cgrp))
3888                         continue;
3889                 if ((cft->flags & CFTYPE_NOT_ON_ROOT) && !cgroup_parent(cgrp))
3890                         continue;
3891                 if ((cft->flags & CFTYPE_ONLY_ON_ROOT) && cgroup_parent(cgrp))
3892                         continue;
3893                 if ((cft->flags & CFTYPE_DEBUG) && !cgroup_debug)
3894                         continue;
3895                 if (is_add) {
3896                         ret = cgroup_add_file(css, cgrp, cft);
3897                         if (ret) {
3898                                 pr_warn("%s: failed to add %s, err=%d\n",
3899                                         __func__, cft->name, ret);
3900                                 cft_end = cft;
3901                                 is_add = false;
3902                                 goto restart;
3903                         }
3904                 } else {
3905                         cgroup_rm_file(cgrp, cft);
3906                 }
3907         }
3908         return ret;
3909 }

3911 static int cgroup_apply_cftypes(struct cftype *cfts, bool is_add)
     /*   */
3912 {
3913         struct cgroup_subsys *ss = cfts[0].ss;
3914         struct cgroup *root = &ss->root->cgrp;
3915         struct cgroup_subsys_state *css;
3916         int ret = 0;
3917 
3918         lockdep_assert_held(&cgroup_mutex);
3919 
3920         /* add/rm files for all cgroups created before */
3921         css_for_each_descendant_pre(css, cgroup_css(root, ss)) {
3922                 struct cgroup *cgrp = css->cgroup;
3923 
3924                 if (!(css->flags & CSS_VISIBLE))
3925                         continue;
3926 
3927                 ret = cgroup_addrm_files(css, cgrp, cfts, is_add);
3928                 if (ret)
3929                         break;
3930         }
3931 
3932         if (is_add && !ret)
3933                 kernfs_activate(root->kn);
3934         return ret;
3935 }

3937 static void cgroup_exit_cftypes(struct cftype *cfts)
     /*   */
3938 {
3939         struct cftype *cft;
3940 
3941         for (cft = cfts; cft->name[0] != '\0'; cft++) {
3942                 /* free copy for custom atomic_write_len, see init_cftypes() */
3943                 if (cft->max_write_len && cft->max_write_len != PAGE_SIZE)
3944                         kfree(cft->kf_ops);
3945                 cft->kf_ops = NULL;
3946                 cft->ss = NULL;
3947 
3948                 /* revert flags set by cgroup core while adding @cfts */
3949                 cft->flags &= ~(__CFTYPE_ONLY_ON_DFL | __CFTYPE_NOT_ON_DFL);
3950         }
3951 }
3952 
3953 static int cgroup_init_cftypes(struct cgroup_subsys *ss, struct cftype *cfts)
     /*   */
3954 {
3955         struct cftype *cft;
3956 
3957         for (cft = cfts; cft->name[0] != '\0'; cft++) {
3958                 struct kernfs_ops *kf_ops;
3959 
3960                 WARN_ON(cft->ss || cft->kf_ops);
3961 
3962                 if (cft->seq_start)
3963                         kf_ops = &cgroup_kf_ops;
3964                 else
3965                         kf_ops = &cgroup_kf_single_ops;
3966 
3967                 /*
3968                  * Ugh... if @cft wants a custom max_write_len, we need to
3969                  * make a copy of kf_ops to set its atomic_write_len.
3970                  */
3971                 if (cft->max_write_len && cft->max_write_len != PAGE_SIZE) {
3972                         kf_ops = kmemdup(kf_ops, sizeof(*kf_ops), GFP_KERNEL);
3973                         if (!kf_ops) {
3974                                 cgroup_exit_cftypes(cfts);
3975                                 return -ENOMEM;
3976                         }
3977                         kf_ops->atomic_write_len = cft->max_write_len;
3978                 }
3979 
3980                 cft->kf_ops = kf_ops;
3981                 cft->ss = ss;
3982         }
3983 
3984         return 0;
3985 }
3986 
3987 static int cgroup_rm_cftypes_locked(struct cftype *cfts)
     /*   */
3988 {
3989         lockdep_assert_held(&cgroup_mutex);
3990 
3991         if (!cfts || !cfts[0].ss)
3992                 return -ENOENT;
3993 
3994         list_del(&cfts->node);
3995         cgroup_apply_cftypes(cfts, false);
3996         cgroup_exit_cftypes(cfts);
3997         return 0;
3998 }

4000 /**
4001  * cgroup_rm_cftypes - remove an array of cftypes from a subsystem
4002  * @cfts: zero-length name terminated array of cftypes
4003  *
4004  * Unregister @cfts.  Files described by @cfts are removed from all
4005  * existing cgroups and all future cgroups won't have them either.  This
4006  * function can be called anytime whether @cfts' subsys is attached or not.
4007  *
4008  * Returns 0 on successful unregistration, -ENOENT if @cfts is not
4009  * registered.
4010  */
4011 int cgroup_rm_cftypes(struct cftype *cfts)
     /*   */
4012 {
4013         int ret;
4014 
4015         mutex_lock(&cgroup_mutex);
4016         ret = cgroup_rm_cftypes_locked(cfts);

4021 /**
4022  * cgroup_add_cftypes - add an array of cftypes to a subsystem
4023  * @ss: target cgroup subsystem
4024  * @cfts: zero-length name terminated array of cftypes
4025  *
4026  * Register @cfts to @ss.  Files described by @cfts are created for all
4027  * existing cgroups to which @ss is attached and all future cgroups will
4028  * have them too.  This function can be called anytime whether @ss is
4029  * attached or not.
4030  *
4031  * Returns 0 on successful registration, -errno on failure.  Note that this
4032  * function currently returns 0 as long as @cfts registration is successful
4033  * even if some file creation attempts on existing cgroups fail.
4034  */
4035 static int cgroup_add_cftypes(struct cgroup_subsys *ss, struct cftype *cfts)
     /*   */
4036 {
4037         int ret;
4038 
4039         if (!cgroup_ssid_enabled(ss->id))
4040                 return 0;
4041 
4042         if (!cfts || cfts[0].name[0] == '\0')
4043                 return 0;
4044 
4045         ret = cgroup_init_cftypes(ss, cfts);
4046         if (ret)
4047                 return ret;
4048 
4049         mutex_lock(&cgroup_mutex);
4050 
4051         list_add_tail(&cfts->node, &ss->cfts);
4052         ret = cgroup_apply_cftypes(cfts, true);
4053         if (ret)
4054                 cgroup_rm_cftypes_locked(cfts);
4055 
4056         mutex_unlock(&cgroup_mutex);
4057         return ret;
4058 }

4119 /**
4120  * css_next_child - find the next child of a given css
4121  * @pos: the current position (%NULL to initiate traversal)
4122  * @parent: css whose children to walk
4123  *
4124  * This function returns the next child of @parent and should be called
4125  * under either cgroup_mutex or RCU read lock.  The only requirement is
4126  * that @parent and @pos are accessible.  The next sibling is guaranteed to
4127  * be returned regardless of their states.
4128  *
4129  * If a subsystem synchronizes ->css_online() and the start of iteration, a
4130  * css which finished ->css_online() is guaranteed to be visible in the
4131  * future iterations and will stay visible until the last reference is put.
4132  * A css which hasn't finished ->css_online() or already finished
4133  * ->css_offline() may show up during traversal.  It's each subsystem's
4134  * responsibility to synchronize against on/offlining.
4135  */
4136 struct cgroup_subsys_state *css_next_child(struct cgroup_subsys_state *pos,
     /*   */
4137                                            struct cgroup_subsys_state *parent)
4138 {
4139         struct cgroup_subsys_state *next;
4140 
4141         cgroup_assert_mutex_or_rcu_locked();
4142 
4143         /*
4144          * @pos could already have been unlinked from the sibling list.
4145          * Once a cgroup is removed, its ->sibling.next is no longer
4146          * updated when its next sibling changes.  CSS_RELEASED is set when
4147          * @pos is taken off list, at which time its next pointer is valid,
4148          * and, as releases are serialized, the one pointed to by the next
4149          * pointer is guaranteed to not have started release yet.  This
4150          * implies that if we observe !CSS_RELEASED on @pos in this RCU
4151          * critical section, the one pointed to by its next pointer is
4152          * guaranteed to not have finished its RCU grace period even if we
4153          * have dropped rcu_read_lock() inbetween iterations.
4154          *
4155          * If @pos has CSS_RELEASED set, its next pointer can't be
4156          * dereferenced; however, as each css is given a monotonically
4157          * increasing unique serial number and always appended to the
4158          * sibling list, the next one can be found by walking the parent's
4159          * children until the first css with higher serial number than
4160          * @pos's.  While this path can be slower, it happens iff iteration
4161          * races against release and the race window is very small.
4162          */
4163         if (!pos) {
4164                 next = list_entry_rcu(parent->children.next, struct cgroup_subsys_state, sibling);
4165         } else if (likely(!(pos->flags & CSS_RELEASED))) {
4166                 next = list_entry_rcu(pos->sibling.next, struct cgroup_subsys_state, sibling);
4167         } else {
4168                 list_for_each_entry_rcu(next, &parent->children, sibling,
4169                                         lockdep_is_held(&cgroup_mutex))
4170                         if (next->serial_nr > pos->serial_nr)
4171                                 break;
4172         }
4173 
4174         /*
4175          * @next, if not pointing to the head, can be dereferenced and is
4176          * the next sibling.
4177          */
4178         if (&next->sibling != &parent->children)
4179                 return next;
4180         return NULL;
4181 }
4182 EXPORT_SYMBOL_GPL(css_next_child);
4183 
4184 /**
4185  * css_next_descendant_pre - find the next descendant for pre-order walk
4186  * @pos: the current position (%NULL to initiate traversal)
4187  * @root: css whose descendants to walk
4188  *
4189  * To be used by css_for_each_descendant_pre().  Find the next descendant
4190  * to visit for pre-order traversal of @root's descendants.  @root is
4191  * included in the iteration and the first node to be visited.
4192  *
4193  * While this function requires cgroup_mutex or RCU read locking, it
4194  * doesn't require the whole traversal to be contained in a single critical
4195  * section.  This function will return the correct next descendant as long
4196  * as both @pos and @root are accessible and @pos is a descendant of @root.
4197  *
4198  * If a subsystem synchronizes ->css_online() and the start of iteration, a
4199  * css which finished ->css_online() is guaranteed to be visible in the
4200  * future iterations and will stay visible until the last reference is put.
4201  * A css which hasn't finished ->css_online() or already finished
4202  * ->css_offline() may show up during traversal.  It's each subsystem's
4203  * responsibility to synchronize against on/offlining.
4204  */
4205 struct cgroup_subsys_state *
4206 css_next_descendant_pre(struct cgroup_subsys_state *pos,
     /*   */
4207                         struct cgroup_subsys_state *root)
4208 {
4209         struct cgroup_subsys_state *next;
4210 
4211         cgroup_assert_mutex_or_rcu_locked();
4212 
4213         /* if first iteration, visit @root */
4214         if (!pos)
4215                 return root;
4216 
4217         /* visit the first child if exists */
4218         next = css_next_child(NULL, pos);
4219         if (next)
4220                 return next;
4221 
4222         /* no child, visit my or the closest ancestor's next sibling */
4223         while (pos != root) {
4224                 next = css_next_child(pos, pos->parent);
4225                 if (next)
4226                         return next;
4227                 pos = pos->parent;
4228         }
4229 
4230         return NULL;
4231 }
4232 EXPORT_SYMBOL_GPL(css_next_descendant_pre);
4233 
4234 /**
4235  * css_rightmost_descendant - return the rightmost descendant of a css
4236  * @pos: css of interest
4237  *
4238  * Return the rightmost descendant of @pos.  If there's no descendant, @pos
4239  * is returned.  This can be used during pre-order traversal to skip
4240  * subtree of @pos.
4241  *
4242  * While this function requires cgroup_mutex or RCU read locking, it
4243  * doesn't require the whole traversal to be contained in a single critical
4244  * section.  This function will return the correct rightmost descendant as
4245  * long as @pos is accessible.
4246  */
4247 struct cgroup_subsys_state *
4248 css_rightmost_descendant(struct cgroup_subsys_state *pos)
     /*   */
4249 {
4250         struct cgroup_subsys_state *last, *tmp;
4251 
4252         cgroup_assert_mutex_or_rcu_locked();
4253 
4254         do {
4255                 last = pos;
4256                 /* ->prev isn't RCU safe, walk ->next till the end */
4257                 pos = NULL;
4258                 css_for_each_child(tmp, last)
4259                         pos = tmp;
4260         } while (pos);
4261 
4262         return last;
4263 }
4264 
4265 static struct cgroup_subsys_state *
4266 css_leftmost_descendant(struct cgroup_subsys_state *pos)
     /*   */
4267 {
4268         struct cgroup_subsys_state *last;
4269 
4270         do {
4271                 last = pos;
4272                 pos = css_next_child(NULL, pos);
4273         } while (pos);
4274 
4275         return last;
4276 }

4278 /**
4279  * css_next_descendant_post - find the next descendant for post-order walk
4280  * @pos: the current position (%NULL to initiate traversal)
4281  * @root: css whose descendants to walk
4282  *
4283  * To be used by css_for_each_descendant_post().  Find the next descendant
4284  * to visit for post-order traversal of @root's descendants.  @root is
4285  * included in the iteration and the last node to be visited.
4286  *
4287  * While this function requires cgroup_mutex or RCU read locking, it
4288  * doesn't require the whole traversal to be contained in a single critical
4289  * section.  This function will return the correct next descendant as long
4290  * as both @pos and @cgroup are accessible and @pos is a descendant of
4291  * @cgroup.
4292  *
4293  * If a subsystem synchronizes ->css_online() and the start of iteration, a
4294  * css which finished ->css_online() is guaranteed to be visible in the
4295  * future iterations and will stay visible until the last reference is put.
4296  * A css which hasn't finished ->css_online() or already finished
4297  * ->css_offline() may show up during traversal.  It's each subsystem's
4298  * responsibility to synchronize against on/offlining.
4299  */
4300 struct cgroup_subsys_state *
4301 css_next_descendant_post(struct cgroup_subsys_state *pos,
     /*   */
4302                          struct cgroup_subsys_state *root)
4303 {
4304         struct cgroup_subsys_state *next;
4305 
4306         cgroup_assert_mutex_or_rcu_locked();
4307 
4308         /* if first iteration, visit leftmost descendant which may be @root */
4309         if (!pos)
4310                 return css_leftmost_descendant(root);
4311 
4312         /* if we visited @root, we're done */
4313         if (pos == root)
4314                 return NULL;
4315 
4316         /* if there's an unvisited sibling, visit its leftmost descendant */
4317         next = css_next_child(pos, pos->parent);
4318         if (next)
4319                 return css_leftmost_descendant(next);
4320 
4321         /* no sibling left, visit parent */
4322         return pos->parent;
4323 }

4326  * css_has_online_children - does a css have online children
4327  * @css: the target css
4328  *
4329  * Returns %true if @css has any online children; otherwise, %false.  This
4330  * function can be called from any context but the caller is responsible
4331  * for synchronizing against on/offlining as necessary.
4332  */
4333 bool css_has_online_children(struct cgroup_subsys_state *css)
     /*   */
4334 {

4336         bool ret = false;

4338         rcu_read_lock();
4339         css_for_each_child(child, css) {
4340                 if (child->flags & CSS_ONLINE) {
4341                         ret = true;
4342                         break;
4343                 }
4344         }

4349 static struct css_set *css_task_iter_next_css_set(struct css_task_iter *it)
     /*   */
4350 {
4351         struct list_head *l;
4352         struct cgrp_cset_link *link;
4353         struct css_set *cset;
4354 
4355         lockdep_assert_held(&css_set_lock);
4356 
4357         /* find the next threaded cset */
4358         if (it->tcset_pos) {
4359                 l = it->tcset_pos->next;
4360 
4361                 if (l != it->tcset_head) {
4362                         it->tcset_pos = l;
4363                         return container_of(l, struct css_set,
4364                                             threaded_csets_node);
4365                 }
4366 
4367                 it->tcset_pos = NULL;
4368         }
4369 
4370         /* find the next cset */
4371         l = it->cset_pos;
4372         l = l->next;
4373         if (l == it->cset_head) {
4374                 it->cset_pos = NULL;
4375                 return NULL;
4376         }
4377 
4378         if (it->ss) {
4379                 cset = container_of(l, struct css_set, e_cset_node[it->ss->id]);
4380         } else {
4381                 link = list_entry(l, struct cgrp_cset_link, cset_link);
4382                 cset = link->cset;
4383         }
4384 
4385         it->cset_pos = l;
4386 
4387         /* initialize threaded css_set walking */
4388         if (it->flags & CSS_TASK_ITER_THREADED) {
4389                 if (it->cur_dcset)
4390                         put_css_set_locked(it->cur_dcset);
4391                 it->cur_dcset = cset;
4392                 get_css_set(cset);
4393 
4394                 it->tcset_head = &cset->threaded_csets;
4395                 it->tcset_pos = &cset->threaded_csets;
4396         }
4397 
4398         return cset;
4399 }

4401 /**
4402  * css_task_iter_advance_css_set - advance a task itererator to the next css_set
4403  * @it: the iterator to advance
4404  *
4405  * Advance @it to the next css_set to walk.
4406  */
4407 static void css_task_iter_advance_css_set(struct css_task_iter *it)
     /*   */
4408 {
4409         struct css_set *cset;
4410 
4411         lockdep_assert_held(&css_set_lock);
4412 
4413         /* Advance to the next non-empty css_set and find first non-empty tasks list*/
4414         while ((cset = css_task_iter_next_css_set(it))) {
4415                 if (!list_empty(&cset->tasks)) {
4416                         it->cur_tasks_head = &cset->tasks;
4417                         break;
4418                 } else if (!list_empty(&cset->mg_tasks)) {
4419                         it->cur_tasks_head = &cset->mg_tasks;
4420                         break;
4421                 } else if (!list_empty(&cset->dying_tasks)) {
4422                         it->cur_tasks_head = &cset->dying_tasks;
4423                         break;
4424                 }
4425         }
4426         if (!cset) {
4427                 it->task_pos = NULL;
4428                 return;
4429         }
4430         it->task_pos = it->cur_tasks_head->next;
4431 
4432         /*
4433          * We don't keep css_sets locked across iteration steps and thus
4434          * need to take steps to ensure that iteration can be resumed after
4435          * the lock is re-acquired.  Iteration is performed at two levels -
4436          * css_sets and tasks in them.
4437          *
4438          * Once created, a css_set never leaves its cgroup lists, so a
4439          * pinned css_set is guaranteed to stay put and we can resume
4440          * iteration afterwards.
4441          *
4442          * Tasks may leave @cset across iteration steps.  This is resolved
4443          * by registering each iterator with the css_set currently being
4444          * walked and making css_set_move_task() advance iterators whose
4445          * next task is leaving.
4446          */
4447         if (it->cur_cset) {
4448                 list_del(&it->iters_node);
4449                 put_css_set_locked(it->cur_cset);
4450         }
4451         get_css_set(cset);
4452         it->cur_cset = cset;
4453         list_add(&it->iters_node, &cset->task_iters);
4454 }

4456 static void css_task_iter_skip(struct css_task_iter *it,
     /*   */
4457                                struct task_struct *task)
4458 {
4459         lockdep_assert_held(&css_set_lock);
4460 
4461         if (it->task_pos == &task->cg_list) {
4462                 it->task_pos = it->task_pos->next;
4463                 it->flags |= CSS_TASK_ITER_SKIPPED;
4464         }
4465 }
4466 
4467 static void css_task_iter_advance(struct css_task_iter *it)
     /*   */
4468 {
4469         struct task_struct *task;
4470 
4471         lockdep_assert_held(&css_set_lock);
4472 repeat:
4473         if (it->task_pos) {
4474                 /*
4475                  * Advance iterator to find next entry. We go through cset
4476                  * tasks, mg_tasks and dying_tasks, when consumed we move onto
4477                  * the next cset.
4478                  */
4479                 if (it->flags & CSS_TASK_ITER_SKIPPED)
4480                         it->flags &= ~CSS_TASK_ITER_SKIPPED;
4481                 else
4482                         it->task_pos = it->task_pos->next;
4483 
4484                 if (it->task_pos == &it->cur_cset->tasks) {
4485                         it->cur_tasks_head = &it->cur_cset->mg_tasks;
4486                         it->task_pos = it->cur_tasks_head->next;
4487                 }
4488                 if (it->task_pos == &it->cur_cset->mg_tasks) {
4489                         it->cur_tasks_head = &it->cur_cset->dying_tasks;
4490                         it->task_pos = it->cur_tasks_head->next;
4491                 }
4492                 if (it->task_pos == &it->cur_cset->dying_tasks)
4493                         css_task_iter_advance_css_set(it);
4494         } else {
4495                 /* called from start, proceed to the first cset */
4496                 css_task_iter_advance_css_set(it);
4497         }
4498 
4499         if (!it->task_pos)
4500                 return;
4501 
4502         task = list_entry(it->task_pos, struct task_struct, cg_list);
4503 
4504         if (it->flags & CSS_TASK_ITER_PROCS) {
4505                 /* if PROCS, skip over tasks which aren't group leaders */
4506                 if (!thread_group_leader(task))
4507                         goto repeat;
4508 
4509                 /* and dying leaders w/o live member threads */
4510                 if (it->cur_tasks_head == &it->cur_cset->dying_tasks &&
4511                     !atomic_read(&task->signal->live))
4512                         goto repeat;
4513         } else {
4514                 /* skip all dying ones */
4515                 if (it->cur_tasks_head == &it->cur_cset->dying_tasks)
4516                         goto repeat;
4517         }
4518 }

4520 /**
4521  * css_task_iter_start - initiate task iteration
4522  * @css: the css to walk tasks of
4523  * @flags: CSS_TASK_ITER_* flags
4524  * @it: the task iterator to use
4525  *
4526  * Initiate iteration through the tasks of @css.  The caller can call
4527  * css_task_iter_next() to walk through the tasks until the function
4528  * returns NULL.  On completion of iteration, css_task_iter_end() must be
4529  * called.
4530  */
4531 void css_task_iter_start(struct cgroup_subsys_state *css, unsigned int flags,
     /*   */
4532                          struct css_task_iter *it)
4533 {
4534         memset(it, 0, sizeof(*it));
4535 
4536         spin_lock_irq(&css_set_lock);
4537 
4538         it->ss = css->ss;
4539         it->flags = flags;
4540 
4541         if (it->ss)
4542                 it->cset_pos = &css->cgroup->e_csets[css->ss->id];
4543         else
4544                 it->cset_pos = &css->cgroup->cset_links;
4545 
4546         it->cset_head = it->cset_pos;
4547 
4548         css_task_iter_advance(it);
4549 
4550         spin_unlock_irq(&css_set_lock);
4551 }

4553 /**
4554  * css_task_iter_next - return the next task for the iterator
4555  * @it: the task iterator being iterated
4556  *
4557  * The "next" function for task iteration.  @it should have been
4558  * initialized via css_task_iter_start().  Returns NULL when the iteration
4559  * reaches the end.
4560  */
4561 struct task_struct *css_task_iter_next(struct css_task_iter *it)
     /*   */
4562 {
4563         if (it->cur_task) {
4564                 put_task_struct(it->cur_task);
4565                 it->cur_task = NULL;
4566         }
4567 
4568         spin_lock_irq(&css_set_lock);
4569 
4570         /* @it may be half-advanced by skips, finish advancing */
4571         if (it->flags & CSS_TASK_ITER_SKIPPED)
4572                 css_task_iter_advance(it);
4573 
4574         if (it->task_pos) {
4575                 it->cur_task = list_entry(it->task_pos, struct task_struct,
4576                                           cg_list);
4577                 get_task_struct(it->cur_task);
4578                 css_task_iter_advance(it);
4579         }
4580 
4581         spin_unlock_irq(&css_set_lock);
4582 
4583         return it->cur_task;
4584 }
4585 
4586 /**
4587  * css_task_iter_end - finish task iteration
4588  * @it: the task iterator to finish
4589  *
4590  * Finish task iteration started by css_task_iter_start().
4591  */
4592 void css_task_iter_end(struct css_task_iter *it)
     /*   */
4593 {
4594         if (it->cur_cset) {
4595                 spin_lock_irq(&css_set_lock);
4596                 list_del(&it->iters_node);
4597                 put_css_set_locked(it->cur_cset);
4598                 spin_unlock_irq(&css_set_lock);
4599         }
4600 
4601         if (it->cur_dcset)
4602                 put_css_set(it->cur_dcset);
4603 
4604         if (it->cur_task)
4605                 put_task_struct(it->cur_task);
4606 }

4627 static void *__cgroup_procs_start(struct seq_file *s, loff_t *pos,
     /*   */
4628                                   unsigned int iter_flags)
4629 {
4630         struct kernfs_open_file *of = s->private;
4631         struct cgroup *cgrp = seq_css(s)->cgroup;
4632         struct css_task_iter *it = of->priv;
4633 
4634         /*
4635          * When a seq_file is seeked, it's always traversed sequentially
4636          * from position 0, so we can simply keep iterating on !0 *pos.
4637          */
4638         if (!it) {
4639                 if (WARN_ON_ONCE((*pos)))
4640                         return ERR_PTR(-EINVAL);
4641 
4642                 it = kzalloc(sizeof(*it), GFP_KERNEL);
4643                 if (!it)
4644                         return ERR_PTR(-ENOMEM);
4645                 of->priv = it;
4646                 css_task_iter_start(&cgrp->self, iter_flags, it);
4647         } else if (!(*pos)) {
4648                 css_task_iter_end(it);
4649                 css_task_iter_start(&cgrp->self, iter_flags, it);
4650         } else
4651                 return it->cur_task;
4652 
4653         return cgroup_procs_next(s, NULL, NULL);
4654 }
4655 
4656 static void *cgroup_procs_start(struct seq_file *s, loff_t *pos)
     /*   */
4657 {
4658         struct cgroup *cgrp = seq_css(s)->cgroup;
4659 
4660         /*
4661          * All processes of a threaded subtree belong to the domain cgroup
4662          * of the subtree.  Only threads can be distributed across the
4663          * subtree.  Reject reads on cgroup.procs in the subtree proper.
4664          * They're always empty anyway.
4665          */
4666         if (cgroup_is_threaded(cgrp))
4667                 return ERR_PTR(-EOPNOTSUPP);
4668 
4669         return __cgroup_procs_start(s, pos, CSS_TASK_ITER_PROCS |
4670                                             CSS_TASK_ITER_THREADED);
4671 }

4679 static int cgroup_may_write(const struct cgroup *cgrp, struct super_block *sb)
     /*   */
4680 {
4681         int ret;
4682         struct inode *inode;
4683 
4684         lockdep_assert_held(&cgroup_mutex);
4685 
4686         inode = kernfs_get_inode(sb, cgrp->procs_file.kn);
4687         if (!inode)
4688                 return -ENOMEM;
4689 
4690         ret = inode_permission(inode, MAY_WRITE);
4691         iput(inode);
4692         return ret;
4693 }
4694 
4695 static int cgroup_procs_write_permission(struct cgroup *src_cgrp,
     /*   */
4696                                          struct cgroup *dst_cgrp,
4697                                          struct super_block *sb)
4698 {
4699         struct cgroup_namespace *ns = current->nsproxy->cgroup_ns;
4700         struct cgroup *com_cgrp = src_cgrp;
4701         int ret;
4702 
4703         lockdep_assert_held(&cgroup_mutex);
4704 
4705         /* find the common ancestor */
4706         while (!cgroup_is_descendant(dst_cgrp, com_cgrp))
4707                 com_cgrp = cgroup_parent(com_cgrp);
4708 
4709         /* %current should be authorized to migrate to the common ancestor */
4710         ret = cgroup_may_write(com_cgrp, sb);
4711         if (ret)
4712                 return ret;
4713 
4714         /*
4715          * If namespaces are delegation boundaries, %current must be able
4716          * to see both source and destination cgroups from its namespace.
4717          */
4718         if ((cgrp_dfl_root.flags & CGRP_ROOT_NS_DELEGATE) &&
4719             (!cgroup_is_descendant(src_cgrp, ns->root_cset->dfl_cgrp) ||
4720              !cgroup_is_descendant(dst_cgrp, ns->root_cset->dfl_cgrp)))
4721                 return -ENOENT;
4722 
4723         return 0;
4724 }
4725 
4726 static int cgroup_attach_permissions(struct cgroup *src_cgrp,
     /*   */
4727                                      struct cgroup *dst_cgrp,
4728                                      struct super_block *sb, bool threadgroup)
4729 {
4730         int ret = 0;
4731 
4732         ret = cgroup_procs_write_permission(src_cgrp, dst_cgrp, sb);
4733         if (ret)
4734                 return ret;
4735 
4736         ret = cgroup_migrate_vet_dst(dst_cgrp);
4737         if (ret)
4738                 return ret;
4739 
4740         if (!threadgroup && (src_cgrp->dom_cgrp != dst_cgrp->dom_cgrp))
4741                 ret = -EOPNOTSUPP;
4742 
4743         return ret;
4744 }

4746 static ssize_t cgroup_procs_write(struct kernfs_open_file *of,
     /*   */
4747                                   char *buf, size_t nbytes, loff_t off)
4748 {
4749         struct cgroup *src_cgrp, *dst_cgrp;
4750         struct task_struct *task;
4751         ssize_t ret;
4752         bool locked;
4753 
4754         dst_cgrp = cgroup_kn_lock_live(of->kn, false);
4755         if (!dst_cgrp)
4756                 return -ENODEV;
4757 
4758         task = cgroup_procs_write_start(buf, true, &locked, dst_cgrp);
4759         ret = PTR_ERR_OR_ZERO(task);
4760         if (ret)
4761                 goto out_unlock;
4762 
4763         /* find the source cgroup */
4764         spin_lock_irq(&css_set_lock);
4765         src_cgrp = task_cgroup_from_root(task, &cgrp_dfl_root);
4766         spin_unlock_irq(&css_set_lock);
4767 
4768         ret = cgroup_attach_permissions(src_cgrp, dst_cgrp,
4769                                         of->file->f_path.dentry->d_sb, true);
4770         if (ret)
4771                 goto out_finish;
4772 
4773         ret = cgroup_attach_task(dst_cgrp, task, true);
4774 
4775 out_finish:
4776         cgroup_procs_write_finish(task, locked);
4777 out_unlock:
4778         cgroup_kn_unlock(of->kn);
4779 
4780         return ret ?: nbytes;
4781 }

4788 static ssize_t cgroup_threads_write(struct kernfs_open_file *of,
     /*   */
4789                                     char *buf, size_t nbytes, loff_t off)
4790 {
4791         struct cgroup *src_cgrp, *dst_cgrp;
4792         struct task_struct *task;
4793         ssize_t ret;
4794         bool locked;
4795 
4796         buf = strstrip(buf);
4797 
4798         dst_cgrp = cgroup_kn_lock_live(of->kn, false);
4799         if (!dst_cgrp)
4800                 return -ENODEV;
4801 
4802         task = cgroup_procs_write_start(buf, false, &locked, dst_cgrp);
4803         ret = PTR_ERR_OR_ZERO(task);
4804         if (ret)
4805                 goto out_unlock;
4806 
4807         /* find the source cgroup */
4808         spin_lock_irq(&css_set_lock);

4810         spin_unlock_irq(&css_set_lock);
4811 
4812         /* thread migrations follow the cgroup.procs delegation rule */
4813         ret = cgroup_attach_permissions(src_cgrp, dst_cgrp,
4814                                         of->file->f_path.dentry->d_sb, false);

4816                 goto out_finish;

4818         ret = cgroup_attach_task(dst_cgrp, task, false);
4819 
4820 out_finish:
4821         cgroup_procs_write_finish(task, locked);
4822 out_unlock:
4823         cgroup_kn_unlock(of->kn);

4825         return ret ?: nbytes;

4921 /*
4922  * css destruction is four-stage process.
4923  *
4924  * 1. Destruction starts.  Killing of the percpu_ref is initiated.
4925  *    Implemented in kill_css().
4926  *
4927  * 2. When the percpu_ref is confirmed to be visible as killed on all CPUs
4928  *    and thus css_tryget_online() is guaranteed to fail, the css can be
4929  *    offlined by invoking offline_css().  After offlining, the base ref is
4930  *    put.  Implemented in css_killed_work_fn().
4931  *
4932  * 3. When the percpu_ref reaches zero, the only possible remaining
4933  *    accessors are inside RCU read sections.  css_release() schedules the
4934  *    RCU callback.
4935  *
4936  * 4. After the grace period, the css can be freed.  Implemented in
4937  *    css_free_work_fn().
4938  *
4939  * It is actually hairier because both step 2 and 4 require process context
4940  * and thus involve punting to css->destroy_work adding two additional
4941  * steps to the already complex sequence.
4942  */
4943 static void css_free_rwork_fn(struct work_struct *work)
     /*   */
4944 {
4945         struct cgroup_subsys_state *css = container_of(to_rcu_work(work),
4946                                 struct cgroup_subsys_state, destroy_rwork);
4947         struct cgroup_subsys *ss = css->ss;
4948         struct cgroup *cgrp = css->cgroup;
4949 
4950         percpu_ref_exit(&css->refcnt);
4951 
4952         if (ss) {
4953                 /* css free path */
4954                 struct cgroup_subsys_state *parent = css->parent;
4955                 int id = css->id;
4956 
4957                 ss->css_free(css);
4958                 cgroup_idr_remove(&ss->css_idr, id);
4959                 cgroup_put(cgrp);
4960 
4961                 if (parent)
4962                         css_put(parent);
4963         } else {
4964                 /* cgroup free path */
4965                 atomic_dec(&cgrp->root->nr_cgrps);
4966                 cgroup1_pidlist_destroy_all(cgrp);
4967                 cancel_work_sync(&cgrp->release_agent_work);
4968 
4969                 if (cgroup_parent(cgrp)) {
4970                         /*
4971                          * We get a ref to the parent, and put the ref when
4972                          * this cgroup is being freed, so it's guaranteed
4973                          * that the parent won't be destroyed before its
4974                          * children.
4975                          */
4976                         cgroup_put(cgroup_parent(cgrp));
4977                         kernfs_put(cgrp->kn);
4978                         psi_cgroup_free(cgrp);
4979                         if (cgroup_on_dfl(cgrp))
4980                                 cgroup_rstat_exit(cgrp);
4981                         kfree(cgrp);
4982                 } else {
4983                         /*
4984                          * This is root cgroup's refcnt reaching zero,
4985                          * which indicates that the root should be
4986                          * released.
4987                          */
4988                         cgroup_destroy_root(cgrp->root);
4989                 }
4990         }
4991 }
4992 
4993 static void css_release_work_fn(struct work_struct *work)
     /*   */
4994 {
4995         struct cgroup_subsys_state *css =
4996                 container_of(work, struct cgroup_subsys_state, destroy_work);
4997         struct cgroup_subsys *ss = css->ss;
4998         struct cgroup *cgrp = css->cgroup;
4999 
5000         mutex_lock(&cgroup_mutex);
5001 
5002         css->flags |= CSS_RELEASED;
5003         list_del_rcu(&css->sibling);
5004 
5005         if (ss) {
5006                 /* css release path */
5007                 if (!list_empty(&css->rstat_css_node)) {
5008                         cgroup_rstat_flush(cgrp);
5009                         list_del_rcu(&css->rstat_css_node);
5010                 }
5011 
5012                 cgroup_idr_replace(&ss->css_idr, NULL, css->id);
5013                 if (ss->css_released)
5014                         ss->css_released(css);
5015         } else {
5016                 struct cgroup *tcgrp;
5017 
5018                 /* cgroup release path */
5019                 TRACE_CGROUP_PATH(release, cgrp);
5020 
5021                 if (cgroup_on_dfl(cgrp))
5022                         cgroup_rstat_flush(cgrp);
5023 
5024                 spin_lock_irq(&css_set_lock);
5025                 for (tcgrp = cgroup_parent(cgrp); tcgrp;
5026                      tcgrp = cgroup_parent(tcgrp))
5027                         tcgrp->nr_dying_descendants--;
5028                 spin_unlock_irq(&css_set_lock);
5029 
5030                 /*
5031                  * There are two control paths which try to determine
5032                  * cgroup from dentry without going through kernfs -
5033                  * cgroupstats_build() and css_tryget_online_from_dir().
5034                  * Those are supported by RCU protecting clearing of
5035                  * cgrp->kn->priv backpointer.
5036                  */
5037                 if (cgrp->kn)
5038                         RCU_INIT_POINTER(*(void __rcu __force **)&cgrp->kn->priv,
5039                                          NULL);
5040         }
5041 
5042         mutex_unlock(&cgroup_mutex);
5043 
5044         INIT_RCU_WORK(&css->destroy_rwork, css_free_rwork_fn);
5045         queue_rcu_work(cgroup_destroy_wq, &css->destroy_rwork);
5046 }
5047 
5048 static void css_release(struct percpu_ref *ref)
     /*   */
5049 {
5050         struct cgroup_subsys_state *css =
5051                 container_of(ref, struct cgroup_subsys_state, refcnt);
5052 
5053         INIT_WORK(&css->destroy_work, css_release_work_fn);
5054         queue_work(cgroup_destroy_wq, &css->destroy_work);
5055 }

5057 static void init_and_link_css(struct cgroup_subsys_state *css,
     /*   */
5058                               struct cgroup_subsys *ss, struct cgroup *cgrp)
5059 {
5060         lockdep_assert_held(&cgroup_mutex);
5061 
5062         cgroup_get_live(cgrp);
5063 
5064         memset(css, 0, sizeof(*css));
5065         css->cgroup = cgrp;
5066         css->ss = ss;
5067         css->id = -1;
5068         INIT_LIST_HEAD(&css->sibling);
5069         INIT_LIST_HEAD(&css->children);
5070         INIT_LIST_HEAD(&css->rstat_css_node);
5071         css->serial_nr = css_serial_nr_next++;
5072         atomic_set(&css->online_cnt, 0);
5073 
5074         if (cgroup_parent(cgrp)) {
5075                 css->parent = cgroup_css(cgroup_parent(cgrp), ss);
5076                 css_get(css->parent);
5077         }
5078 
5079         if (cgroup_on_dfl(cgrp) && ss->css_rstat_flush)
5080                 list_add_rcu(&css->rstat_css_node, &cgrp->rstat_css_list);
5081 
5082         BUG_ON(cgroup_css(cgrp, ss));
5083 }

5085 /* invoke ->css_online() on a new CSS and mark it online if successful */
5086 static int online_css(struct cgroup_subsys_state *css)
     /*   */
5087 {
5088         struct cgroup_subsys *ss = css->ss;
5089         int ret = 0;
5090 
5091         lockdep_assert_held(&cgroup_mutex);
5092 
5093         if (ss->css_online)
5094                 ret = ss->css_online(css);
5095         if (!ret) {
5096                 css->flags |= CSS_ONLINE;
5097                 rcu_assign_pointer(css->cgroup->subsys[ss->id], css);
5098 
5099                 atomic_inc(&css->online_cnt);
5100                 if (css->parent)
5101                         atomic_inc(&css->parent->online_cnt);
5102         }
5103         return ret;
5104 }
5105 
5106 /* if the CSS is online, invoke ->css_offline() on it and mark it offline */
5107 static void offline_css(struct cgroup_subsys_state *css)
     /*   */
5108 {
5109         struct cgroup_subsys *ss = css->ss;
5110 
5111         lockdep_assert_held(&cgroup_mutex);
5112 
5113         if (!(css->flags & CSS_ONLINE))
5114                 return;
5115 
5116         if (ss->css_offline)
5117                 ss->css_offline(css);
5118 
5119         css->flags &= ~CSS_ONLINE;
5120         RCU_INIT_POINTER(css->cgroup->subsys[ss->id], NULL);
5121 
5122         wake_up_all(&css->cgroup->offline_waitq);
5123 }

5125 /**
5126  * css_create - create a cgroup_subsys_state
5127  * @cgrp: the cgroup new css will be associated with
5128  * @ss: the subsys of new css
5129  *
5130  * Create a new css associated with @cgrp - @ss pair.  On success, the new
5131  * css is online and installed in @cgrp.  This function doesn't create the
5132  * interface files.  Returns 0 on success, -errno on failure.
5133  */
5134 static struct cgroup_subsys_state *css_create(struct cgroup *cgrp,
     /*   */
5135                                               struct cgroup_subsys *ss)
5136 {
5137         struct cgroup *parent = cgroup_parent(cgrp);
5138         struct cgroup_subsys_state *parent_css = cgroup_css(parent, ss);
5139         struct cgroup_subsys_state *css;
5140         int err;
5141 
5142         lockdep_assert_held(&cgroup_mutex);
5143 
5144         css = ss->css_alloc(parent_css);
5145         if (!css)
5146                 css = ERR_PTR(-ENOMEM);
5147         if (IS_ERR(css))
5148                 return css;
5149 
5150         init_and_link_css(css, ss, cgrp);
5151 
5152         err = percpu_ref_init(&css->refcnt, css_release, 0, GFP_KERNEL);
5153         if (err)
5154                 goto err_free_css;
5155 
5156         err = cgroup_idr_alloc(&ss->css_idr, NULL, 2, 0, GFP_KERNEL);
5157         if (err < 0)
5158                 goto err_free_css;
5159         css->id = err;
5160 
5161         /* @css is ready to be brought online now, make it visible */
5162         list_add_tail_rcu(&css->sibling, &parent_css->children);
5163         cgroup_idr_replace(&ss->css_idr, css, css->id);
5164 
5165         err = online_css(css);
5166         if (err)
5167                 goto err_list_del;
5168 
5169         if (ss->broken_hierarchy && !ss->warned_broken_hierarchy &&
5170             cgroup_parent(parent)) {
5171                 pr_warn("%s (%d) created nested cgroup for controller \"%s\" which has incomplete hierarchy support. Nested cgroups may change behavior in the future.\n",
5172                         current->comm, current->pid, ss->name);
5173                 if (!strcmp(ss->name, "memory"))
5174                         pr_warn("\"memory\" requires setting use_hierarchy to 1 on the root\n");
5175                 ss->warned_broken_hierarchy = true;
5176         }
5177 
5178         return css;
5179 
5180 err_list_del:
5181         list_del_rcu(&css->sibling);
5182 err_free_css:
5183         list_del_rcu(&css->rstat_css_node);
5184         INIT_RCU_WORK(&css->destroy_rwork, css_free_rwork_fn);
5185         queue_rcu_work(cgroup_destroy_wq, &css->destroy_rwork);
5186         return ERR_PTR(err);
5187 }
